<subSubSection lastPageId="31" lastPageNumber="100" pageId="30" pageNumber="99" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="30.[151,1437,1555,2013]" pageId="30" pageNumber="99">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,324,1590,1616]" pageId="30" pageNumber="99">Diagnosis:</emphasis>
main song of 
<specimenCount box="[494,595,1591,1617]" pageId="30" pageNumber="99" type="generic" typeStatus="type">one type</specimenCount>
, elements long and flattened and rather slow-paced (n = 2, 
<figureCitation box="[1284,1354,1591,1617]" captionStart="FIGURE 2" captionStartId="11.[151,250,1697,1721]" captionTargetBox="[388,1205,925,1672]" captionTargetId="figure-251@11.[378,1210,921,1673]" captionTargetPageId="11" captionText="FIGURE 2. The seven element shapes found in the Cacomantis variolosus complex. Taxon names given represent the following geographic song types (see Results): sepulcralis—Sundaland and Philippines, virescens—Sulawesi and Sula, aeruginosus—resident Moluccas, variolosus—Australasia, blandus—Admiralty Islands, addendus—Solomon Islands." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5840531" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5840531/files/figure.png" pageId="30" pageNumber="99">Fig. 2</figureCitation>
); basic morph of Admiralties morphotype (see 3.2.2.(4) above); body small and tail proportionally mid-length: wing c. 
<quantity box="[151,302,1662,1689]" metricMagnitude="-1" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.105" metricValueMax="1.15" metricValueMin="1.06" pageId="30" pageNumber="99" unit="mm" value="110.5" valueMax="115.0" valueMin="106.0">106–115 mm</quantity>
, tail/wing ratio 0.96–1.02 (
<tableCitation box="[609,696,1663,1689]" captionStart="TABLE 2" captionStartId="3.[151,244,466,493]" captionTargetBox="[165,2020,579,1643]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="TABLE 2. Measurements and proportions of regional forms and populations of the Cacomantis variolosus complex. Bracketed measurements are of extreme ranges; those in between cover 75% of variation. Records of numbers of morphs per population are not exhaustive because morphs were not recorded for all museum collections. Abbreviations: M—males, F—females." httpUri="http://table.plazi.org/id/DF346630FFBEFFA086B269F4FDDDFD91" pageId="30" pageNumber="99" tableUuid="DF346630FFBEFFA086B269F4FDDDFD91">Table 2</tableCitation>
); barred females with dorsa dully barred dusky on greyish cinnamon, and ventral white distinct, barred discretely black without cinnamon wash; juveniles intermediate in depth of tones and density of markings, but whiter ventrally than in other differentiates (n = 1). Element shape of song notes is unique except for those in the Solomon differentiate 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Rothschild &amp; Hartert" authorityYear="1901" box="[761,900,1771,1797]" class="Aves" family="Cuculidae" genus="Cacomantis" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Cuculiformes" pageId="30" pageNumber="99" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="addendus">
<emphasis box="[761,900,1771,1797]" italics="true" pageId="30" pageNumber="99">C. addendus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<figureCitation box="[915,984,1771,1797]" captionStart="FIGURE 2" captionStartId="11.[151,250,1697,1721]" captionTargetBox="[388,1205,925,1672]" captionTargetId="figure-251@11.[378,1210,921,1673]" captionTargetPageId="11" captionText="FIGURE 2. The seven element shapes found in the Cacomantis variolosus complex. Taxon names given represent the following geographic song types (see Results): sepulcralis—Sundaland and Philippines, virescens—Sulawesi and Sula, aeruginosus—resident Moluccas, variolosus—Australasia, blandus—Admiralty Islands, addendus—Solomon Islands." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5840531" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5840531/files/figure.png" pageId="30" pageNumber="99">Fig. 2</figureCitation>
; see below). The bill is also distinctively broad, and this, together with tail proportions, are shared with Bismarck populations and arguably indicative of its derivation (
<tableCitation box="[279,367,1843,1869]" captionStart="TABLE 2" captionStartId="3.[151,244,466,493]" captionTargetBox="[165,2020,579,1643]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="TABLE 2. Measurements and proportions of regional forms and populations of the Cacomantis variolosus complex. Bracketed measurements are of extreme ranges; those in between cover 75% of variation. Records of numbers of morphs per population are not exhaustive because morphs were not recorded for all museum collections. Abbreviations: M—males, F—females." httpUri="http://table.plazi.org/id/DF346630FFBEFFA086B269F4FDDDFD91" pageId="30" pageNumber="99" tableUuid="DF346630FFBEFFA086B269F4FDDDFD91">Table 2</tableCitation>
; also 
<bibRefCitation author="Mayr, E. &amp; Diamond, J." box="[431,755,1842,1869]" pageId="30" pageNumber="99" refId="ref25907" refString="Mayr, E. &amp; Diamond, J. (2001) The Birds of Northern Melanesia: Speciation, Ecology, and Biogeography. Oxford University Press, Oxford, xxiv + 492 pp." type="book" year="2001">Mayr &amp; Diamond 2001: 235</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="30.[151,1437,1555,2013]" lastBlockId="31.[151,1437,150,249]" lastPageId="31" lastPageNumber="100" pageId="30" pageNumber="99">
The greyer dorsum and sharply demarcated grey-and-rufous ventral surface in 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Rothschild &amp; Hartert" authorityYear="1914" box="[1073,1194,1879,1905]" class="Aves" family="Cuculidae" genus="Cacomantis" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Cuculiformes" pageId="30" pageNumber="99" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="blandus">
<emphasis box="[1073,1194,1879,1905]" italics="true" pageId="30" pageNumber="99">C. blandus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
are also unique in the complex, resembling east Asian C. 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Scopoli" baseAuthorityYear="1786" box="[552,664,1915,1941]" class="Aves" family="Cuculidae" genus="Cacomantis" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Cuculiformes" pageId="30" pageNumber="99" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="merulinus">
<emphasis box="[552,664,1915,1941]" italics="true" pageId="30" pageNumber="99">merulinus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and leading 
<bibRefCitation author="Rothschild, W. &amp; Hartert, E." box="[810,1145,1915,1942]" pageId="30" pageNumber="99" pagination="281 - 298" refId="ref27186" refString="Rothschild, W. &amp; Hartert, E. (1914 b) The birds of the Admiralty Islands, north of German New Guinea. Novitates Zoologicae, 21, 281 - 298." type="journal article" year="1914">Rothschild &amp; Hartert (1914b)</bibRefCitation>
to query affinities. White barring in outer rectrices, however, is altogether different—fine teeth in 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Rothschild &amp; Hartert" authorityYear="1914" box="[990,1079,1951,1977]" class="Aves" family="Cuculidae" genus="Cacomantis" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Cuculiformes" pageId="30" pageNumber="99" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="blandus">
<emphasis box="[990,1079,1951,1977]" italics="true" pageId="30" pageNumber="99">blandus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and complete diagonal bars in 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Scopoli" baseAuthorityYear="1786" box="[151,263,1987,2013]" class="Aves" family="Cuculidae" genus="Cacomantis" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Cuculiformes" pageId="30" pageNumber="99" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="merulinus">
<emphasis box="[151,263,1987,2013]" italics="true" pageId="30" pageNumber="99">merulinus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. So is the main song, which in 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Scopoli" baseAuthorityYear="1786" box="[618,730,1987,2013]" class="Aves" family="Cuculidae" genus="Cacomantis" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Cuculiformes" pageId="30" pageNumber="99" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="merulinus">
<emphasis box="[618,730,1987,2013]" italics="true" pageId="30" pageNumber="99">merulinus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="S. Muller" baseAuthorityYear="1843" box="[763,886,1987,2013]" class="Aves" family="Cuculidae" genus="Cacomantis" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Cuculiformes" pageId="30" pageNumber="99" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="sepulcralis">
<emphasis box="[763,886,1987,2013]" italics="true" pageId="30" pageNumber="99">sepulcralis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
-like except for falling away in a bubbled jumble of notes at the end. 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Rothschild &amp; Hartert" authorityYear="1914" box="[371,493,151,177]" class="Aves" family="Cuculidae" genus="Cacomantis" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Cuculiformes" pageId="31" pageNumber="100" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="blandus">
<emphasis box="[371,493,151,177]" italics="true" pageId="31" pageNumber="100">C. blandus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
has been treated as a subspecies of 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Vigors &amp; Horsfield" baseAuthorityYear="1827" box="[894,1011,151,177]" class="Aves" family="Cuculidae" genus="Cacomantis" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Cuculiformes" pageId="31" pageNumber="100" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="variolosus">
<emphasis box="[894,1011,151,177]" italics="true" pageId="31" pageNumber="100">variolosus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
by all reviewers since 
<bibRefCitation author="Hartert, E." box="[1268,1431,150,177]" pageId="31" pageNumber="100" pagination="164 - 174" refId="ref24871" refString="Hartert, E. (1925) Review of the genus Cacomantis Mull. Novitates Zoologicae, 32, 164 - 174. https: // doi. org / 10.5962 / bhl. part. 4504" type="journal article" year="1925">Hartert (1925)</bibRefCitation>
, based on morphology alone; and its respective phenotypic and vocal similarities to 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Scopoli" baseAuthorityYear="1786" box="[1084,1196,187,213]" class="Aves" family="Cuculidae" genus="Cacomantis" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Cuculiformes" pageId="31" pageNumber="100" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="merulinus">
<emphasis box="[1084,1196,187,213]" italics="true" pageId="31" pageNumber="100">merulinus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and Solomon 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Rothschild &amp; Hartert" authorityYear="1901" class="Aves" family="Cuculidae" genus="Cacomantis" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Cuculiformes" pageId="31" pageNumber="100" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="addendus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="31" pageNumber="100">addendus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
could be either convergent or retained ancestral traits.
</paragraph>
